Owner: HR / IT / Security
Approved By: CEO

1. Purpose
This checklist ensures that when an employee or contractor leaves Kahana, their access is promptly revoked, company assets are returned, and data is handled securely. It supports SOC 2 requirements for user access revocation and information security during terminations.

2. Scope
Applies to:

All employees, contractors, and interns whose engagement with Kahana ends (voluntary or involuntary).

All systems, devices, and physical access associated with Kahana work.

3. Offboarding Steps (Checklist)
You can turn this into a table in Notion/Sheets. Each line should have: “Owner, Due date, Done (Y/N), Notes.”

A. Initiation (HR / Manager)
 Offboarding request created in HR/IT system with last working day and time.

 IT/Security notified in advance of departure (or immediately for involuntary termination).

 List of systems and access reviewed (SSO directory, password manager, vendor inventory, etc.).

B. Logical Access Revocation (IT / Security)
Perform as close as possible to the effective termination time (earlier for high‑risk cases).

 Disable account in primary identity provider (Google Workspace; internal IdP for Adam and team).

 Revoke access to:

Email and collaboration: Google Workspace, Slack, Discord.

Kahana Oasis admin tools and production access: AWS, Supabase, GitHub, CI/CD.

VPN and remote access tools (if applicable).

Other SaaS: Tally.so, Google Sheets, Mixpanel, Stripe, ProductHunt, CRM, ticketing, monitoring, etc.

 Invalidate active sessions, tokens, and API keys associated with the user where possible.
​

 Remove from mailing lists, groups, and shared calendars.
​

For privileged and technical staff, also:

 Rotate any shared credentials or admin passwords the user knew.

 Review and, if needed, rotate secrets/keys created by the user (e.g., in secrets manager).

C. Data and Ownership Transfer (Manager / IT)
 Transfer ownership of important documents, repositories, and accounts (e.g., shared drives, project boards, admin roles) to another owner before full account deletion.
​

 Ensure customer‑facing responsibilities and open tickets are reassigned.

 Decide what to do with email (forwarding to manager, auto‑reply, or mailbox export) consistent with law and policy.

D. Physical Access and Assets (Operations / Manager)
 Recover all company‑owned devices: laptops, monitors, phones, hardware tokens, USB keys, etc.

 Recover building access badges, keys, or other physical access devices.

 Remove or update physical access rights (door codes, access lists).
​

 Confirm devices will be wiped, reimaged, or securely stored before reassignment.

E. HR & Admin Close‑Out (HR / Finance)
 Update HR system and payroll to reflect termination date.
​

 Cancel or adjust expense cards, benefits, and other financial accounts.
​

 Update organizational chart and internal directories.

F. Confirmation and Recordkeeping
 Manager and HR review that all steps are completed.

 Offboarding checklist signed/approved by HR and IT/Security (electronically is fine).

 Checklist and related evidence (screenshots/exports, ticket links) stored in the employee’s HR/security file as SOC 2 evidence.

4. Timeliness
Per Access Control Policy: All access must be revoked within 24 hours of termination or contract end.

For involuntary or high‑risk departures, access should be revoked immediately at decision time, coordinated between HR and IT/Security (or Adam/CEO for small team).

5. Review and Maintenance
This checklist is reviewed at least annually, or when tools and systems change, to ensure all key systems and steps remain covered.